### Explanation of the Proof

1. **`add_mem'`**: To prove that the intersection of two ideals is closed under addition, take any `x ∈ I ∩ J` and `y ∈ I ∩ J`. Then `x ∈ I`, `x ∈ J`, `y ∈ I`, and `y ∈ J`. Since `I` and `J` are ideals, `x + y ∈ I` and `x + y ∈ J`. Thus, `x + y ∈ I ∩ J`.

2. **`zero_mem'`**: The zero element is in every ideal, so `0 ∈ I` and `0 ∈ J`, hence `0 ∈ I ∩ J`.

3. **`smul_mem'`**: For any scalar `c ∈ R` and any `x ∈ I ∩ J`, we have `x ∈ I` and `x ∈ J`. Since `I` and `J` are ideals, `c • x ∈ I` and `c • x ∈ J`, so `c • x ∈ I ∩ J`.

